Link in my bio 😁 // Nintendo's handhelds may have dominated my childhood, but that doesn't mean I didn't get to have some wonderful memories playing on the other consoles haha! Spider-Man 2 on the PS2 was probably my first taste of an open-world sandbox game. And almost two decades later, I wanted to revisit the experience through Insomniac's Spider-Man Miles Morales on the PlayStation 5. 

For me, the best advantage of the PS5 over its predecessors is the loading times. Coming from handhelds, I just can't stand how long home consoles used to load. But with the PS5, it felt like playing a DS where loading times are much more reasonable. Now that's what a fast console is, and totally justifies home consoles today having to install the game on a drive.

"Bathala Creating the World"

There were many gods in the precolonial Tagalog pantheons to which our ancestors prayed and worshipped. But none of those gods compared to the one at the highest, even outside the realm of this world. Out of reverence, people chose not to ask him favors unless needed. There were the lower gods for that. So best leave the dirty work to them. The dignity of this god, who created everything that was shaped, is above our measly earthly affairs.

His name is Bathalang Maykapal, the indigenous Tagalog version of the god with the G, the supreme deity, Brahman, Elohim. And he is the one represented in these wallpapers which I'm sharing with you now.

Apologies for taking so long. I was, and still am, worried about the ethics of sharing images generated by AI due to them being derivatives of preexisting and unattributed human artworks. In retrospect, even the ethics of my use of the AI tool is also in question. So for the longest time, the most they serve as are personal wallpapers for my screens.

With that, I'd appreciate it if anyone could name the artists from whose artworks these images might have been derived. The least I could do is credit them.

Cheers 🙏

Watch a Gundam Builder try building an IKEA Living Room Set! Link in my bio 😁 // I got so invested in the making of the IKEA Fjallbo Set that I thought it deserves its own separate post where it's not just a twist to the main subject haha. 

The idea of getting the Fjallbo is actually spurned by my 55" TV that I used to have in my room. Finding it too big, I decided to just give it to the whole household. The problem is, we don't have anywhere to put it on; it's too big for our tables. And so, we got the Fjallbo TV Unit. Getting a PS5 further justified the move; it's very chonky, and looks really disproportionate when placed on the table we have.

To complete the look and make it a proper makeover, we also got the shelf unit, coffee table, and carpet. What wasn't really mentioned in the video was the Yeelight LED Strip that I put behind the Fjallbos. Figured it would be a fun surprise near the end hahaha

I honestly wanted to put a voiceover in this like that homemade pandesal video we made a while back, but I think it would not really contribute to the tone I'm going for and might hurt it in fact. But what do you think of the video? hahaha

After more than 2 years since our last major Plamo video (Unicorn Gundam), we’re finally back on building again! Since that time, we’ve seen many in the community embracing the Beat Building format, showcasing their process with the help of crispy cuts and sounds, and we couldn’t be more grateful! 

And so, to show our excitement and appreciation, we will try, with this project, to put a twist on the format. The keyword there is ‘try’, because there’s no guarantee of success. Should we not succeed, we would still end up with a build project that’s just as special and extensive as our past major builds. But if all goes well, and we sure hope it does, this project might end up becoming an evolution of Beat Building.

Thank you so much for your patience and continuous support, everyone! See you soon!

CASETiFY iPhone 15 Cases is now available at CASETiFY! Go to https://www.casetify.com/giosanpedro (link also in my bio) and use the promo code "15GIOSANPEDRO" to get 10% off your order today!

To be honest, I had no plans to upgrade this year. But due to the prospect of having a USB-C phone again, and computational photography that can finally put up a fight against the Google Pixel, I just had to reconsider! And true enough, the camera (the software that is) of the iPhone 15 Pro can finally go head-to-head with Pixel, so much so that I found myself shooting in RAW less often, if at all. The contoured edges make the phone feel thinner than it is. It's lighter for sure, but not remarkably so. Bezels are noticeably thinner, but they also don't make any difference in day-to-day use.

In line with having everything USB-C, we also got the AirPods Pro with an updated port. Sadly, I had to have it serviced because, for some reason, its sound quality is a tad worse than my Gen 2 Pros last year. Hopefully, they acknowledge the issue.

Lastly,  the Apple Watch Series 9 may look identical outside, but it is considerably faster now, the animation is smoother, the screen is brighter, and now instead of Graphite, I went with Silver since it's the color compatible with most watch bands available.

Its 50mp main camera is now gimbal-stabilized. The front cam is now 32mp. Obviously, if I get the chance to have a deeper hand-on of it, I wanna do a real-world test of its photographic capabilities. Right now, there is no mobile game that's too heavy for phones as capable as this one, even at Max settings.
